SIMPLE: ignore
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ignore
<hw>Ig*nore"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Ignored</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ignoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>ignorare</ets>; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> not + the root of <ets>gnarus</ets> knowing,
<ets>noscere</ets> to become acquainted with. See <er>Know</er>, and cf.
<er>Narrate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be ignorant of or not
acquainted with.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Philosophy would solidly be established, if men would more
carefully distinguish those things that they know from those that they
<qex>ignore</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To throw out or reject as false or
ungrounded; -- said of a bill rejected by a grand jury for lack of
evidence. See <er>Ignoramus</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence: To refuse to take notice of; to shut the eyes
to; not to recognize; to disregard willfully and causelessly; <as>as, to
<ex>ignore</ex> certain facts; to <ex>ignore</ex> the presence of an
objectionable person.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Ignoring</qex> Italy under our feet,⟦br⟧
And seeing things before, behind.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ignoscible</ent>⟦br⟧
